Enbridge Local: Edmonton Terminal, Alberta-International Boundary near Gretna, Manitoba

splitDescription.Enbridge FSP: Shippers pay international joint tolls for crude oil shipped from Canada to the U.S. on the Flanagan South Pipeline System. These tolls are based on volumes, the various pipeline routes (combinations of receipt and delivery points) and the qualities of the crude oil to be shipped.
splitDescription.Enbridge Local: Shippers pay Canadian tolls for crude oil shipped solely within Canada. These tolls are based on volumes, the various pipeline routes (combinations of receipt and delivery points) and the qualities of the crude oil to be shipped.
splitDescription.Enbridge Mainline:
Canadian Mainline tolls are set according to the Competitive Toll Settlement (CTS), a 10-year negotiated settlement that went into effect on July 1, 2011 and expired on June 30, 2021. It established tolls for all volumes shipped on the Canadian Mainline as well as International Joint Tariff (IJT). The tolls are fixed, however, they are adjusted annually with the gross domestic product index. Because tolls are fixed, if throughput decreases Enbridge faces additional financial risks compared to the previous cost of service tolling method. 

Under the CTS, the Enbridge Mainline provides entirely uncommitted capacity to its shippers. In December 2019, Enbridge filed an application with the CER for approval of a new service and tolling framework, seeking to have it in place when the current CTS expires. Enbridge proposes to offer long-term contracts on the Mainline for up to 90% of the capacity, with at least 10% of capacity remaining available for uncommitted service [Folder 3895249].
